properties.location: Loddon River downstream of Kerang and Bendigo & Bullock Creeks
properties.webBody:
Moderate Flood Warning for the Loddon River

  • MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT APPIN SOUTH FROM SUNDAY MORNING AND KERANG FROM OVERNIGHT MONDAY. PEAK FLOOD LEVELS SIMILAR TO JAN 2011 POSSIBLE. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING IS CONTINUING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LODDON WEIR 
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in the Loddon River catchment, with renewed rises from recent rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream. 
  • Major flooding is continuing at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir, and is likely to extend downstream to Appin South from Sunday morning and to Kerang from overnight Monday into Tuesday. River levels are likely to peak at similar levels to the January 2011 flood event. 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Laanecoorie Reservoir and minor flooding is occurring Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran.
Bendigo and Bullock Creeks:
River levels are elevated along the Bendigo and Bullock Creeks.

Loddon River downstream of Kerang:
River levels are elevated along the Loddon River downstream of Kerang.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Avoid contact with any floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other contaminants
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be impacted by floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service 

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (Vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon.
This Advice replaces the advice message issued at 13.22PM

MAJOR FLOODING NOW OCCURRING AT SHEPPARTON WHERE A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 12.00 METRES IS POSSIBLE ON TUESDAY
MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR AND MURCHISON

Major flooding has developed along the Goulburn River at Shepparton during Saturday afternoon, with levels rising rapidly due to tributary inflows from the Broken River and Seven and Castle Creeks. 

River levels will continue to rise as the main flood peak arrives along the Goulburn River from Murchison, with a peak around 12.00 metres possible on Tuesday.

Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. 

Major flooding is currently peaking around 12.00 metres at Murchison.

Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.

Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon:
Minor flooding is continuing along the Goulburn River upstream of Lake Eildon at Dohertys during Saturday.


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.  
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Donâ€™t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be affected by flooding. For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au
  • Animals are taking refuge on roadways drive with caution and remain vigilant of wildlife 
  • Due to recent rainfalls roads have significantly deteriorated drive with extreme caution
  • No heavy vehicles on Goulburn Valley Highway to Shepparton use alternate route to Wangaratta via Bundalong on the Murray Valley Highway
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.

If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000 If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500


Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for Orrvale. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

  • This updated evacuation advice replaces the Emergency Warning issued at 6pm, due to reviewing the flood conditions.
  • It is now recommended that residents and visitors in Orrvale evacuate between now and 11pm Saturday 15th October to the Shepparton Showgrounds, High St Shepparton.
  • This advice particularly applies to:
Properties along Broken River Drive to Archer St down to Oxbow Ave (south side) along the southern edge of Kensington Gardens across to McPhees Rd; east to Doyles Rd to Orrvale Rd to Prentice Rd across Central Ave up to Channel Rd to Jameson Rd across to Boundary Rd and to the East Goulburn Main Channel. Then south to where the Channel meets the No 8 Main Channel then up to River Rd to Trevaskis Rd. Across to Doyles Rd continuing across to Archer Rd and into areas including Avon St, Wilgarning Dve, Whitton Ave, Marlboro Dve, Kerang Ave and areas along the Kialla Lakes.
If you are located in Orrvale, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately to the Shepparton Showgrounds.
If you are already surrounded by floodwater, it is too late to leave.
Never enter floodwater.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • The relief centre that has been opened at Shepparton Showgrounds. 
  • Family or friendsâ€™ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.

The Midland Highway, also known as the Mooroopna Causeway between Mooroopna and Shepparton is now CLOSED.

When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications.

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

This warning is current to 11pm Saturday 15th October. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Based on historic data, this flood is likely to have a similar impact as the 1974 flood event.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 11:30 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point .

Minor flooding is occurring along the Ovens River Bright to Rocky Point.


  • The Ovens River at Eurobin is currently steady at 4.54 metres, with minor flooding. 
  • The Ovens River at Eurobin will fall below the minor flood level (4.50 m) around midday Saturday.
  • The Ovens River at Rocky Point peaked at 4.20 metres around 01:00 am Saturday 15 October and is currently at 4.05 metres and steady. 
  • The Ovens River at Rocky Point is expected to remain above the minor flood level (3.20 m) during Saturday.

This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 3.56 AM Saturday 15/10/2022 .
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  •  Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads will be affected by flooding
  • Go to https://traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/ for any traffic updates

Eurobin
  • Below the Minor Flood level Initial breakouts from the Ovens River south-west of Selzers Lane toward the Great Alpine Road / Happy Valley Creek (Mummery Break) may still be flooded. 
  • Water over the road at Standish Street.
  • At the Minor Flood Level (4.5m) commencement of main break from the Ovens River toward Happy Valley Creek upstream of Selzers Lane, leading to increased flow through Myrtleford
Myrtleford
  • At Minor Flood Level, the Ovens River overflows at Selzers Lane (Ovens) and many other places between the Hop Gardens and Myrtleford-this may still be flooded.
  •  Flooding in Myrtleford is inevitable once the Ovens River overflows upstream of town. 
  • Standish Street floodway will be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 11:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.

For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River downstream of Charlton. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT CHARLTON TOWN WITH A PEAK AROUND 8.0 METRES OVERNIGHT SUNDAY INTO MONDAY
  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT YAWONG WEIR, WHERE RENEWED RISES ARE OCCURRING AND DOWNSTREAM (D/S) CHARLTON TOWN
  • MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT QUAMBATOOK
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Avoca River at Yawong Weir, where renewed rises are occurring, at Charlton Town and at Downstream (D/S) Charlton Town.
  • Minor flooding is occurring at Quambatook as the floodwaters arrive from last week's rainfall. Renewed rises from this week's rainfall are expected early next week.
Avoca River downstream of Charlton Town:
Major flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Charlton Town. Minor flooding is occurring at Quambatook.

The Avoca River at Quambatook is currently at 2.04 metres and slowly falling, with minor flooding. Renewed rises are expected early next week.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • There will be several low level farm crossings which intersect rivers that will be inundated. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 08:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.location: Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN THE 2016 FLOOD AND SIMILAR TO OR EXCEEDING THE 1993 FLOOD POSSIBLE AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA FROM WEDNESDAY
  • Heavy rainfall overnight Thursday into Friday has resulted in rapid river level rises and major flooding along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers.
  • These flood waters combined with flows down the Murray Rivers are expected to cause major flooding at Echuca and Moama from this week (19-21 October). River levels at Echuca Wharf may exceed the 2016 flood (93.39 m AHD) and reach levels possibly higher than the 1993 flood (94.77 m AHD). As this flood water moves downstream, river level rises and significant major flooding is expected at Torrumbarry and Barham.
  • Forecasts will be updated as upstream peaks are observed along the along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers. Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream along the Murray River will be refined once there is more certainty in the expected peak at Echuca Wharf.
  • Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.
Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:
Major flooding is expected at Echuca, Moama and Torrumbarry. Major flooding is occurring at Barham.

The Murray River at Echuca Wharf is expected to exceed the minor flood level (93.5 metres), during Sunday. The river level is likely to exceed the major flood level (94.40 m AHD) from around Wednesday or Thursday and may reach around 95.00 metres AHD around 20-23 October, with major flooding. This level similar to the October 1993 flood event. Further rises are possible.

The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may reach around 7.85 metres around 24-29 October, with major flooding. This is higher than the January 1974 flood. Further rises possible.

The Murray River at Barham may reach 6.20 metres in the last week of October, with major flooding. This is higher than the October 1993 and 2016 floods. Further rises possible.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW & Victoria. for more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and  www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.

WATCH & ACT - RIVERINE FLOOD - Move to Higher Ground
Incident Location: Murray River downstream of Tocumwal
Issue Date: Saturday 15 October 2022, 04:45 pm
Next Update: Sunday 16 October 2022, 01:30 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/23399/moreinfo

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham. 

- MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN THE 2016 FLOOD AND SIMILAR TO OR EXCEEDING THE 1993 FLOOD POSSIBLE AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA FROM WEDNESDAY
- Heavy rainfall overnight Thursday into Friday has resulted in rapid river level rises and major flooding along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers.
- These flood waters combined with flows down the Murray Rivers are expected to cause major flooding at Echuca and Moama from this week (19-21 October). River levels at Echuca Wharf may exceed the 2016 flood (93.39 m AHD) and reach levels possibly higher than the 1993 flood (94.77 m AHD). As this flood water moves downstream, river level rises and significant major flooding is expected at Torrumbarry and Barham.
- Forecasts will be updated as upstream peaks are observed along the along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers. Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream along the Murray River will be refined once there is more certainty in the expected peak at Echuca Wharf.
- Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies. 

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:
Major flooding is expected at Echuca, Moama and Torrumbarry. Major flooding is occurring at Barham.

The Murray River at Echuca Wharf is expected to exceed the minor flood level (93.5 metres), during Sunday. The river level is likely to exceed the major flood level (94.40 m AHD) from around Wednesday or Thursday and may reach around 95.00 metres AHD around 20-23 October, with major flooding. This level similar to the October 1993 flood event. Further rises are possible.

The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may reach around 7.85 metres around 24-29 October, with major flooding. This is higher than the January 1974 flood. Further rises possible.

The Murray River at Barham may reach 6.20 metres in the last week of October, with major flooding. This is higher than the October 1993 and 2016 floods. Further rises possible. 

Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Rupanyup and Dunmunke Creek. 

Water levels along Dunmunkle Creek have been steeply rising from early today, as water moves away from the Flood impacted areas around Glenorchy.

Rupanyup 
Flooding may impact the Rupanyup Golf Course. 

Deep flooding may cut access to roads along Dunmunkle Creek in and surrounding Rupanyup
  • Boyds Road,

A cold front has crossed Victoria resulting in a widespread heavy falls during Wednesday into early Friday. 

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet and river levels are elevated within the catchments. 

No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days. 

Widespread minor to major flooding is occurring in several catchments across Victoria. 
Major flood warnings are current for the Avoca, Broken, Campaspe, Goulburn, Ovens and King, Loddon, Wimmera, Seven and Castle Creeks. Moderate flood warnings are current for the Barwon River, Mt Emu Creek and Yarra River. A minor to major flood warning is current for the Murray River. Minor flood warnings are current for the Bunyip, Kiewa, Latrobe, Mitchell, Werribee and Broken Creek.

Thomson River 
South Gippsland Rivers

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point to Wangaratta
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point to Wangaratta.


MAJOR FLOODING TO CONTINUE AT WANGARATTA  DURING SATURDAY

Major flooding has peaked downstream on the Ovens River at Wangaratta overnight Friday into Saturday.

The flood evacuation warning for Parfitt Road, Wangaratta has been lifted.

Community meeting
A community meeting will be held at St. Patrick's Hall, Ford Street Wangaratta (Opposite Big W) today, Saturday October 15, at 4pm. 


Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:
Major flooding is occurring along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta peaked at 12.78 metres around 02:00 am Saturday 15 October, with major flooding and is currently at 12.76 metres and slowly falling. 
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is expected to remain above the major flood level (12.70 m) during Saturday. 
  • The river level may fall below the major flood level (12.70 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday.


This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 3:56 AM, Saturday 15/10/2022. 
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.

Please keep children away from playing within floodwaters. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home or sheds is likely to occur in some locations.   
 Above the Major Flood Level at (12.8m )
  • A number of properties are at risk of above floor flooding
  • Merriwa Park Inundated, floodwater could be up to 2m deep in some areas
  • Increased access issues to driveways and home along Oxley Flats Rd
  • Access issues beginning to properties Bowser Rd
  • Floodwaters may begin to breach the Parfitt Road levee but do not impact on dwellings at this level
At Major flood level (12.7 m)
  • Water up to Yogis nose
  • Painters Island caravan park is closed. 
  • Extensive road closures. 
  • Widespread flooding occurs around the airport and along the Ovens River flats north of Wangaratta to Peechelba.
  • Water over many roads including: Parfitt, Bowser, Vernon, Lucas, Fraser, Wylie, Melba, Sunset, Trotman, Walter and willow drive.
At the Moderate Flood Level (12.4m) 
  • Residents in Wilson and Parfitt Road levees are advised to implement their Flood Emergency Plans. 
  • The Great Alpine Rd is likely to close near Wangaratta, traffic detour is via Detour Rd. 
  • Extensive flooding through APEX Park.  
  • Bickerton St carpark closed and access road to Painters Island Caravan Park flooded.  
  • Shallow flooding to Pinkerton Cres and backyards along Templeton St and Baker St
At the Minor Flood Level (11.9m) 
  •  Apex Park and farmland along the Ovens, King and possibly the Fifteen Mile Creek floodplains north, south and east of Wangaratta begin flooding.  
  •  Bike paths and walking tracks around and downstream of Apex Park and the Northern Beaches are closed.  
  • Many riverside carparks are closed including Sydney Beach, Bickerton St and Baker St. 

There will be water over the road at many locations, including:
  • Parfitt and Bowser Roads, north of the levee system
  • Vernon Road
  • Lucas Street
  • Carboor-Everton Road, between Markwood-Everton Road and Snow Road
  • Fraser Lane
  • Wylie Street
  • Melba Drive
  • Sunset Drive
  • Trotman Drive
  • Walter Street
  • Willow Drive

As river heights increase, there may be other impacts across many areas of Wangaratta.

MAJOR FLOODING TO CONTINUE AT WANGARATTA  DURING SATURDAY 

Major flooding has peaked downstream on the Ovens River at Wangaratta overnight Friday into Saturday. 

The flood evacuation warning for Parfitt Road, Wangaratta has been lifted. 

Community meeting
A community meeting will be held at St. Patrick's Hall, Ford Street Wangaratta (Opposite Big W) today, Saturday October 15, at 4pm. 


Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:
Major flooding is occurring along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

properties.location: Gippsland Lakes and the Gippsland Coast from McLoughlins Beach to Marlo
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for water in the Gippsland Lakes and the Ninety Mile Beach from McLoughlins Beach to Marlo.

  • The levels of blue green algae within the Gippsland Lakes have decreased to well below the safe contact thresholds. The entire Gippsland Lakes system and Ninety Mile Beach is now safe for recreational contact with water.
  • However as toxins from the algae can accumulate in seafood after a bloom has dispersed, advice regarding the consumption of specific seafood still applies.
  • The latest seafood sample results show that Nodularin concentrations remain elevated in crab and bug samples collected within and outside the Gippsland Lakes. Additional seafood samples are being organised for collection and analysis.
Do not consume crustaceans (such as prawns, crabs and bugs) and shellfish caught inside the Gippsland Lakes or within 10 nautical miles of the shore between Mcloughlins Beach and Marlo. 

Finfish caught from within the Gippsland Lakes should be rinsed thoroughly in fresh water and the guts and gills removed before cooking or freezing.

Ingesting these toxins can lead to serious illness. Cooking or freezing does not destroy thetoxins.
What you should do:
  • Visit betterhealth.vic.gov.au (https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/harmful-algal-blooms) for more information.
  • Keep up-to-date with algae information at www.water.vic.gov.au/waterways-and-catchments/rivers-estuaries-and-waterways/blue-green-algae

Protect your health:
  • If you are experiencing any health issues after contact with affected water seek medical advice from your local doctororNurse-On-Call (https://www2.health.vic.gov.au/primary-and-community-health/primary-care/nurse-on-call)on 1300 606 024.

This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 19/10/2022 03:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Information about blue green algae:
  • For information on blue green algae visit: www2.health.vic.gov.au/public-health/water/blue-green-algae-cyanobac teria.

properties.webBody:
This Community information is being issued for Echuca.

  • This Community information replaces the Water Quality Advice message issued at 12:44 PM on Friday, 14 October.. 
  • Water quality testing has confirmed that the water supply in these suburbs is now safe to drink.   
  • It is recommended that your run your internal taps for 2 minutes to flush out old water and draw fresh water into your plumbing. 
  • Coliban Water, following consultation with the Department of Health, advises customers that the Boil Water Advisory issued on Thursday 13 October 2022 is now lifted for Echuca. The water is safe to drink. 
  • The Boil Water Advisory was issued following excessive stormwater due to inclement weather entering one of our treated water storage tanks. This may have compromised the safety of the drinking water.
  • The Advisory is now lifted after the tank was isolated and flushing of the supply system completed. Water quality testing has confirmed the water supply is safe.
  • If you have any questions, please call Coliban Water on 1300 363 200.
NOTE: we are aware of a technical issue with the previous Advice message for this same incident which is still appearing on VicEmergency.  We are working to have this removed.
This message was issued by Department of Health.

There are no further updates expected.

Health information: 
  • If you need medical advice for exposure to contaminated water, seek medical advice or call Nurse on Call on 1300 606 024.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte.
  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 6 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 3 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 14 October 2022.
  •  Insignificantkrainfall totals are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 15 October 2022.
Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte
  • The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently at 4.52 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (4.10metres), and rising.
  • It is expected to peak around the Moderate Flood Level (4.60 metres) overnight Saturday(15 October 2022)
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 06:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

This is a Final Minor Flood Warning for  Mitta Mitta River Downstream of Lake Dartmouth.

MINOR FLOODING NO LONGER EXPECTED AT TALLANDOON   

Elevated river levels are occurring along the Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth but minor flooding is no longer expected at Tallandoon   

  • In the 24 hours to 8:00 am Saturday, rainfall totals of 5-15 mm have been recorded in the Mitta Mitta River catchment. 
  • No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days.  
  •  The Mitta Mitta River at Tallandoon is currently at 3.64 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. The Mitta Mitta River at Tallandoon is expected to remain below the minor flood level (4.20 m). 

 This  final Advice replaces the Advice issued at 1.36 PM Friday October 14   
The threat of flooding is reduced. Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and beware of hazards remaining in the warning area.
What you should do:

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If your home or business has been flooded:
  • Check for building damage before you enter.
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For emergency assistance from the SES call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Damage to roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Lake Eppalock to Barnadown.

  • MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN JAN 2011 FLOOD EVENT IS OCCURRING ALONG THE CAMPASPE RIVER
  • MAJOR FLOODING PEAKED AT ROCHESTER TOWN OVERNIGHT FRIDAY INTO SATURDAY
  • Widespread major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Lake Eppalock and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday. Major flooding is occurring at Barnadown and Rochester Town. River levels are exceeding those experienced during the January 2011 flood event. 
  • Goulburn Murray Water advises that Lake Eppalock is full and spilling, with flows receding at Downstream (D/S) Lake Eppalock.
Campaspe River Lake Eppalock to Barnadown: 

Major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River Lake Eppalock to Barnadown.

No observations are currently available on the Campaspe River D/S Lake Eppalock. The river level is expected to be below the moderate flood level (160.40 m AHD), with minor flooding continuing. 

No observations are currently available on the Campaspe River at Barnadown. The river level is likely to have peaked during Friday morning above the Jan 2011 flood level, with major flooding. The Campaspe River at Barnadown is expected to remain above the major flood level (5.00 m) during Saturday and Sunday.

A relief centre is open at Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Street, Bendigo.
Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 

Major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River Lake Eppalock to Barnadown. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  •  Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  •  Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Heavy rainfall has resulted in significant runoff and flooding in local creeks and streams.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Homes and towns are likely to be isolated.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay.  

Major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River Lake Eppalock to Barnadown. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground.

properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for properties within the township of Mooroopna. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

  • This updated evacuation advice replaces the Emergency Warning issued at 6:01pm, due to reviewing the flood conditions.
  • It is now recommended that residents and visitors in Mooroopna evacuate between now and 11pm Saturday 15th October to the Ballantyne Centre, 9 Hastie St, Tatura.
  • This advice particularly applies to:
From Cemetery Rd south to Hoggard Dve including Little Rd down to the Echuca Rd around the back of properties on Paisley Crt; along the edge of the Conservation Reserve to the power sub-station then along Echuca Rd to Grange St; South to Macisaac Rd across to Norton Reserve and along Norton Dve around Homewood Dve at the back of Westview Dve to the rear of the Rodney Park Retirement Village to Knight St. south across to Jones Drive along the western side of Rodney Park Reserve then across McLennan St to Emma St, Hall St, Daisy St to Lenne St along Stanley St along the rear of properties along Rostrata Cr, following the reserve to Banfield Ave (S/E side). Then across to the reserve along the Goulburn River - follow the river north across the highway to Cemetery Rd again.
If you are located in Mooroopna, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately to the Ballantyne Centre, 9 Hastie St, Tatura.
If you are already surrounded by floodwater, it is too late to leave.
Never enter floodwaters.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • The relief centre that has been opened at the Ballantyne Centre, 9 Hastie St, Tatura. 
  • Family or friendsâ€™ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
The Midland Highway also known as the Mooroopna Causeway between Shepparton and Mooroopna is now CLOSED.

When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

This warning is current to 11pm Saturday 15th October. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Based on historic data, this flood is likely to have a similar impact as the 1974 flood event.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 11:30 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Echuca. 
  • Coliban Water, following consultation with the Department of Health, advises that customers in Echuca should boil their drinking water until further notice.   
  • This advisory has been issued following excessive stormwater due to inclement weather entering one of our treated water storage tanks. 
  • This may compromise the safety of the drinking water. The tank has now been isolated.
  • Coliban Water will keep customers informed as the situation changes.
  • This Advice replaces the Advice issued at 12.49pm, Thursday 13 October, 2022.
If you are live or work within Echuca, you must boil tap water before drinking.
What you should do:

  • Coliban Water recommends customers should bring water to a rolling boil before being used by heating the water until a continuous and rapid stream of air bubbles is produced from the bottom of a pan or kettle. 
  • Kettles with automatic cut-off switches are suitable. Variable temperature kettles should be set to boil.     
  • After heating, water must be allowed to cool before using it, and be stored in a clean, closed container for later use. 
  • Care should be taken to avoid scalding injuries especially around children.       
Boiled water can be used for:  
  • Drinking  
  • Preparing beverages  
  • Washing and preparing food  
  • Preparing baby formula  
  • Brushing teeth  
  • Making ice.  
Unboiled water can be used for:
  • Washing your hands
  • Showering and bathing
  • Flushing toilets
  • Washing dishes (ensure dry before use)
  • Clothes and garden watering. 
Ensure water is not ingested whilst bathing.  

  • Consumption of unboiled water can cause gastro-like symptoms. If you experience any of these symptoms, please contact your GP and inform your GP of this advisory.  
  • Please share this advice with neighbours and friends in the affected area. 
  • Would owners of rented properties please ensure your tenants are aware of this advisory.
Impacts in your area:
  • If a water quality issue is detected, Coliban Water will work to address the issue and keep customers informed.
This message was issued by the Department of Health. 

The next update is expected by 12pm, 17 October or as the situation changes.    

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Quantong and Lower Norton. 

Wimmera River at Quantong (downstream of Horsham)

Minor flooding is occurring along the Wimmera River downstream of Horsham.

The Wimmera River at Quantong Bridge is above the minor flood level.  Renewed rises are likely from Monday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.        
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 17/10/2022 11:50 am or as the situation changes.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Mitchell River downstream of Glenaladale 

Minor Flood Warning for the Mitchell River 

MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT BAIRNSDALE SATURDAY EVENING 

Minor flooding has eased at Glenaladale but minor flooding may develop along the Mitchell River at Bairnsdale Saturday evening. 

No significant rainfall is forecast across the catchment for the remainder of the weekend. 

Mitchell River downstream of Glenaladale: 

Minor flooding may occur along the Mitchell River downstream of Glenaladale. 

The Mitchell River at Bairnsdale is currently at 3.08 meters and rising, below the minor flood level. The Mitchell River at Bairnsdale may peak around the minor flood level (4.0 m) Saturday evening.

Wonnangatta River: 

Minor flooding is occurring along the Wonnangatta River to Waterford. 

Mitchell River to Glenaladale: 

Minor flooding has eased along the Mitchell River at Glenaladale. The Mitchell River at Glenaladale is currently at 2.97 meters and falling, below the minor flood level (3.0 m) after a peak of 3.0 meters early Saturday morning. 
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.location: Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon Weir to Kerang.

  • MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT APPIN SOUTH FROM SUNDAY MORNING AND KERANG FROM OVERNIGHT MONDAY. PEAK FLOOD LEVELS SIMILAR TO JAN 2011 POSSIBLE. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING IS CONTINUING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LODDON WEIR
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in the Loddon River catchment, with renewed rises from recent rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream. 
  • Major flooding is continuing at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir, and is likely to extend downstream to Appin South from Sunday morning and to Kerang from overnight Monday into Tuesday. River levels are likely to peak at similar levels to the January 2011 flood event. 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Laanecoorie Reservoir and minor flooding is occurring Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran.
Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang: 
Major flooding is occurring along the Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang. The Loddon River at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is currently nearing a peak around 7.25 metres, with major flooding. 

The Loddon River at Appin South is currently at 3.24 metres and rising, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is likely to exceed the major flood level (3.30 m) Sunday morning. The river level may reach around 3.50 metres during Monday, close to the January 2011 flood peak of 3.57 metres. 

The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is currently at 76.79 (m AHD) metres and rising slowly, below the minor flood level (77.00 m AHD). The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge (Kerang) is likely to exceed the minor flood level (77.00 m AHD) Sunday morning. The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (77.50 m AHD) Monday afternoon and is likely to exceed the major flood level (77.80 m AHD) overnight Monday into Tuesday. River levels may reach around 78.0 m AHD overnight Tuesday into Wednesday, similar to the levels reached in the January 2011 flood event.
Appin South could be impacted anytime Sunday morning. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  •  Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  •  Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
  •  Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Widespread flooding of the area.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River to Charlton Town. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT CHARLTON TOWN WITH A PEAK AROUND 8.0 METRES OVERNIGHT SUNDAY INTO MONDAY
  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT YAWONG WEIR, WHERE RENEWED RISES ARE OCCURRING AND DOWNSTREAM (D/S) CHARLTON TOWN
  • MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT QUAMBATOOK
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Avoca River at Yawong Weir, where renewed rises are occurring, at Charlton Town and at Downstream (D/S) Charlton Town.
  • Minor flooding is occurring at Quambatook as the floodwaters arrive from last week's rainfall. Renewed rises from this week's rainfall are expected early next week.
Avoca River to Charlton Town: 
Major flooding is occurring along the Avoca River to Charlton Town.

The Avoca River at Charlton Town is currently at 7.67 metres and rising, with major flooding. The Avoca River at Charlton Township may peak near 8.00 metres overnight Sunday into Monday.
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • There will be several low level farm crossings which intersect rivers that will be inundated.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 10:00 pm 15/10/2022 or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Campaspe river Barnadown to Rochester.

  • MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN JAN 2011 FLOOD EVENT IS OCCURRING ALONG THE CAMPASPE RIVER
  • MAJOR FLOODING PEAKED AT ROCHESTER TOWN OVERNIGHT FRIDAY INTO SATURDAY 
  • Widespread major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Lake Eppalock and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday. Major flooding is occurring at Barnadown and Rochester Town. River levels are exceeding those experienced during the January 2011 flood event. Goulburn Murray Water advises that Lake Eppalock is full and spilling, with flows receding at Downstream (D/S) Lake Eppalock.
Campaspe River Barnadown to Rochester: 
Major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River Barnadown to Rochester. 

The Campaspe River at Rochester Town peaked at 115.65 metres around midnight Friday into Saturday and is currently at 115.41 metres and steady, with major flooding. 

The Campaspe River at Rochester Town is likely to remain above the major flood level (114.50 m) during Saturday and Sunday. 

A relief centre is open at Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Street, Bendigo.
Campaspe River Barnadown to Rochester could be impacted.  Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous. Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services. 
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  •  Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  •  Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  •  Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Widespread flooding of the area. 
  • Homes and towns are likely to be isolated. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.location: Broken River downstream of Casey Weir
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the Broken River downstream of Casey Weir. 

MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT ORRVALE, WITH A MAJOR FLOOD PEAK AROUND 8.3 METRES POSSIBLE SUNDAY MORNINGMINOR FLOODING AT CASEY WEIR AND BENALLA
River levels along the Broken River have peaked at Benalla and Casey Weir, where minor flooding is continuing. The flood peak is now upstream of Orrvale, where major flooding is now occurring, with a peak around 8.3 metres possible on Sunday morning.
Rainfall has eased, and no significant rainfall is forecast during the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.

Broken River downstream of Casey Weir
Major flooding is expected along the Broken River downstream of Casey Weir.
The Broken River at Orrvale is currently at 7.95 metres and rising, with major flooding. The Broken River at Orrvale may peak near 8.30 metres Sunday morning.


This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 02.49PM, Saturday 15/10/2022. 


Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Access the Benalla Flood Guide Here
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
Above the Moderate (7.2m) to the Major Flood Level (7.9m)
  • Some properties may experience over-floor flooding at Archer Road, Kialla West
  • Gordon Drive is likely to be closed
  • Innundation of land in Hooper Rd, Kialla
  • Water over the Northern Causeway on Archer Street
  • Further over-floor flooding on Doyles Road and Jamieson Road, Jamieson Road likely to be closed
  • Archer Road, south of Kialla Lakes Drive, may be over-topped by overflow from Broken River anabranch
  • Residents north and east of Lake Kialla and east of Lake Amaroo may become isolated. 
At the Minor (6.8m) and Moderate (7.2m) Flood Levels
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • The Midland Highway east of Shepparton may be affected flooding
  • Rural properties upstream of Doyles Road may become flooded
  • Gordon Drive (Broken River anabranch) may be over-topped at the western end by waters flowing out of Lake Kialla.
  • Lake Amaroo may over top and Kialla Lakes Drive becomes affected by flooding

This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 02:50 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.

Flood Recovery Hotline Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.  Call 1800 560 760

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for Murchison. 

  • An Evacuation Warning remains current, but it is now too late to leave. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR AND MURCHISON
  • MAJOR FLOODING NOW OCCURRING AT SHEPPARTON WHERE A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 12.00 METRES IS POSSIBLE ON TUESDAY
  • Major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.
  • The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently peaking around 12.00 metres, with major flooding. The Goulburn River at Murchison will remain above the major flood level (10.70 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
  • The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 11.03 metres and rising, with major flooding. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is likely to exceed 11.50 metres around 11:00 pm Saturday. The river level may reach around 12.00 metres during Tuesday..
  • This Emergency Warning replaces the Emergency Warning issued 1.08PM 15 October
It is now too late to leave for people in Murchison. If you have not evacuated, you should shelter in the highest location possible.
What you should do: 

If you have not already evacuated: 
  • Stay where you are and shelter in the highest location possible. 
  • Be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time. 
  • If floodwater has entered your home or you are isolated, remain on higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance. 

If you have already evacuated: 
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued. 
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Campaspe River Downstream of Rochester.

  • MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN JAN 2011 FLOOD EVENT IS OCCURRING ALONG THE CAMPASPE RIVER
  • MAJOR FLOODING PEAKED AT ROCHESTER TOWN OVERNIGHT FRIDAY INTO SATURDAY 
  • Widespread major flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Lake Eppalock and its tributaries in response to widespread heavy rainfall during Wednesday and Thursday. Major flooding is occurring at Barnadown and Rochester Town. River levels are exceeding those experienced during the January 2011 flood event. 
  • Goulburn Murray Water advises that Lake Eppalock is full and spilling, with flows receding at Downstream  Lake Eppalock. 
Campaspe River downstream of Rochester: 
Minor to major flooding is expected to continue along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester during Saturday and Sunday. The Campaspe River at Rochester Syphon is currently peaking around 9.3 m, with major flooding. The Campaspe River at Echuca is above the minor flood level (92.80 m AHD) and rising. The river level is likely to peak around 95.8 m AHD during Sunday morning, with major flooding. The peak will be prolonged due to elevated Murray River levels. This level is higher than during the Jan 2011 flood event.

A relief Centre is open at Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Street Bendigo
Echuca could be impacted anytime Sunday Morning. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  •  Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  •  Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Widespread flooding of the area.
  • Homes and towns are likely to be isolated.
  •  Some areas will be likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Wimmera River Catchment. 

The Wimmera river is expected to peak at Horsham Monday morning, at approximately 8.30am. 

Flood impacts are likely to start to occur in Riverside overnight Saturday and into Sunday.   

Impacts on roads and properties, as water levels rise will occur from Saturday evening through Sunday and Monday morning.    

In preparation for the expected flood levels, people should be aware of possible impacts.    

Significant flooding is likely to occur through Horsham and Riverside with properties that may be impacted with above floor flooding.  Current predictions are for flood heights to be between the 1 in 20 and 1 in 50 year Annual Exceedance Probability (AEP) flood events.    

Potential areas that may be impacted include 
  • Eastern end of Hamilton Street through to the Horsham Botanic Gardens and Wotonga Basin.  
  • Horsham Riverside Caravan Park 
  • Horsham Showgrounds 
  • Schools along the river area 
  • Access to Sunnyside Lutheran Retirement Village and Kurrajong Lodge Retirement Village.     
Refer to the Horsham Local Flood Guide for more information and you can access Horsham Flood Extent maps here.     
 
Horsham roads that may be impacted with possible deep floodwaters include
  • Hamilton Street Riverside 
  • Road Pryors road 
  • Peppertree Lane 
  • Barnes Boulevard 
  • Eastgate Drive 
  • Macbain Street 
  • Gillespie Street 
  • Robinson Street 
  • Menadue Street 
  • Trinity Drive 
  • Baillie Street 
  • Stockton Drive 
  • Williams Road    
Riverside road areas impacted with possible deep floodwaters include
  • Heards Road 
  • Peels Road 
  • School Road Riverside 
  • East Road 
  • Cameron Road 
  • Riverside Road 
Shallow flooding is likely for West Road, Horsham Lubeck Road, Browns Road, Rokeskys Road.

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.


What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:

  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.    
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.
