properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MAJOR FLOODING NOW OCCURRING AT SHEPPARTON WHERE A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 12.00 METRES IS POSSIBLE ON TUESDAY MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR AND MURCHISON

Major flooding has developed along the Goulburn River at Shepparton during Saturday afternoon, with levels rising rapidly due to tributary inflows from the Broken River and Seven and Castle Creeks. 
River levels will continue to rise as the main flood peak arrives along the Goulburn River from Murchison, with a peak around 12.00 metres possible on Tuesday.
Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres.
Major flooding is currently peaking around 12.00 metres at Murchison.
Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.

Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton:
Major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.
The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently peaking around 12.00 metres, with major flooding. 
The Goulburn River at Murchison will remain above the major flood level (10.70 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 11.03 metres and rising, with major flooding. 
The Goulburn River at Shepparton is likely to exceed 11.50 metres around 11:00 pm Saturday. The river level may reach around 12.00 metres during Tuesday.






The next warning will be issued by 01:00am 16 October 2022.



Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and NEVER  enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.


If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • No heavy vehicles on Goulburn Valley Highway to Shepparton use alternate route to Wangaratta via Bundalong on the Murray Valley Highway
  •  Due to recent rainfalls roads have significantly deteriorated drive with extreme caution 
  •  Animals are taking refuge on roadways drive with caution and remain vigilant of wildlife 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Further information can be accessed from the Mooroopna and Shepparton flood guide at ses.vic.gov.au
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.


Flood Warning Number: 13
MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT KIALLA WEST WITH A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 7.2 METRES SATURDAY NIGHTMINOR FLOODING CONTINUING TO EASE AT EUROA.
Moderate flooding has eased at upstream locations along the Seven and Castle Creek with major flooding now extending downstream to Kialla West.
No significant rainfall is forecast for the remainder of the weekend.

Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa:
Major flooding is occurring along the Seven Creeks downstream of Euroa.
The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is currently at 7.16 metres with major flooding. The Seven Creeks at Kialla West is expected to peak around 7.20 metres Saturday night, higher than September 2010 (6.65 m).
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.
What you should do: 

Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.

If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.     
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Campaspe downstream of Rochester.

  • Due to major flooding of the Campaspe River, widespread flooding is occurring East of the Campapse river downstream of Rochester. 

  • Move to higher ground if safe to do so or shelter in place if unsafe to leave.

Communities of Nanneella, Fairy Dell, Koyuga and Kanyapella Southare currently being impacted. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground if safe to do so.  
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  •  Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  •  Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • Homes and towns are likely to be isolated.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for Charlton Township. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

  • Floodwaters are rapidly rising. 
  • Major flooding is expected to impact Charlton township on Sunday 16 October 2022.
  • The duration of the event is likely to be 3-5 days.
If you are located in the Charlton Township, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately. 
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • The relief centre that has been opened at Wycheproof P-12 College, McKenzie Cr, Wycheproof. The facility may have capabilities for small domestic pets, preferably in cages.
  • Family or friendsâ€™ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • The safest evacuation route is by Calder Highway, but continue to check regular updates via the VicTraffic website.
  • When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

This warning is current to 10am Sunday 16th October 2022. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to, is dangerous and may put your life at risk. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for the Hopkins River downstream of Hexham and Mt Emu Creek downstream of Darlington.

ELEVATED RIVER LEVELS ARE LIKELY ON THE HOPKINS RIVER THROUGH HOPKINS FALLS AND DOWNSTREAM THROUGH ALLANSFORD AND WARRNAMBOOL

  • Major flooding has eased along the Mt Emu Creek at Skipton and moderate flooding is now occurring.
  • Elevated river levels can be expected over the next several days from Saturday 15th October.
  • Higher river levels can be expected to continue for a number of days.
  • Communities along the Hopkins River and Mt Emu Creek should stay informed of their local risk.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
 What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/ and download the VicEmergency
  • Check for road closures on the VicRoads website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au)
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Flood Recovery Hotline
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with
  • navigating available supports 
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.  

If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance, Call 000 
If your home is about to flood, Call VICSES on 132 500

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie. 

  • MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT APPIN SOUTH FROM SUNDAY MORNING AND KERANG FROM OVERNIGHT MONDAY. PEAK FLOOD LEVELS SIMILAR TO JAN 2011 POSSIBLE. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING IS CONTINUING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LODDON WEIR 
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in the Loddon River catchment, with renewed rises from recent rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream. 
  • Major flooding is continuing at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir, and is likely to extend downstream to Appin South from Sunday morning and to Kerang from overnight Monday into Tuesday. River levels are likely to peak at similar levels to the January 2011 flood event. 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Laanecoorie Reservoir and minor flooding is occurring Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran.
Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie: 

Minor flooding is occurring along the Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie.

The Loddon River D/S Cairn Curran is currently at 2.29 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Loddon River D/S Cairn Curran is likely to remain above the minor flood level (2.00 m) during Saturday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.       
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for downstream of Barham to Wentworth.

MAJOR FLOODING HIGHER THAN THE 2016 FLOOD AND SIMILAR TO OR EXCEEDING THE 1993 FLOOD POSSIBLE AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA FROM LATE NEXT WEEK

Heavy rainfall overnight Thursday into Friday has resulted in rapid river level rises and major flooding along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers. These flood waters combined with flows down the Murray Rivers are expected to cause major flooding at Echuca and Moama from mid next week (19-21 October). 

River levels at Echuca Wharf may exceed the 2016 flood (93.39 m AHD) and reach levels similar to or possibly higher than the 1993 flood (94.77 m AHD) towards the end of next week (21-24 October). As this flood water moves downstream, river level rises and significant major flooding is expected at Torrumbarry and Barham.

Forecasts will be updated as upstream peaks are observed along the along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers. 

Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream along the Murray River will be provided once there is more certainty in the expected peak at Echuca Wharf.

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth: 
  • Minor flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Wakool Junction and is possible at Boundary Bend and Wentworth.
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction may reach near 9.70 metres around over the weekend, with minor flooding.
  • The Murray River at Boundary Bend is likely to reach the minor flood level (8.00 metres) during Saturday.
  • The Murray River at Wentworth may reach the minor flood level (32.08 m AHD) around 19-22 October.
This updated Advice message replaces the Advice issued at 4:11pm on Thursday 13/10/2022. 

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in New South Wales and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting wwww.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnâ€™t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels may cause flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some agricultural land may be vulnerable to flooding. Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Local roads may be closed.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

Note for information: Major flooding higher than the 2016 flood and similar to or exceeding the 1993 flood possible at Echuca and Moama from Wednesday

Heavy rainfall overnight Thursday into Friday has resulted in rapid river level rises, and includes major flooding along the Goulburn and Campaspe Rivers. 

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. 

MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:

Moderate flooding is occurring along the Murray River at Corowa. Moderate flooding is possible Yarrawonga, minor possible at Tocumwal.

The Murray River at Albury peaked at 4.21 metres around 02:00 am Saturday 15 October, below the minor flood level (4.30 metres) and is currently at 4.18 metres, below the minor flood level and steady.

The Murray River at Corowa is expected to reach around 6.20 metres during Monday, with moderate flooding.

Subject to the forecast inflows from the Ovens River, the Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream is likely to exceed the minor flood level (6.40 m) during Monday. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (6.70 m) during Wednesday and may reach around 7.10 metres on Thursday with minor flooding.Further rises are possible.

The Murray River at Tocumwal is likely to exceed the minor flood level (6.40 m) during Tuesday. The river level may reach 6.50 metres during Thursday with minor flooding. Further rises are possible.



  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
  • Much of the flooding impacts is occurring on the NSW side of the Murray River
  • Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
  • For more information relevant to your area please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria  
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move immediately to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • Parks, tracks and campgrounds maybe closed due to flooding
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
ROAD CLOSURES
  • Murray Valley Highway between the Hume Freeway and Rutherglen has been closed due to floodwater. 
  • Local roads may be closed due to impact of flood waters. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 01:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

- Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria. 
- Much of the flooding impacts is occurring on the NSW side of the Murray River
- Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.
- For more information relevant to your area please check www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria  

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.

properties.name: Warning
properties.webBody:
This Warning is being issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek
 and replaces the warning issued yesterday for the same event. 

  • A landslide has occurred on the Bogong - High Plains Road at Bogong Village.
  • There is a slow moving active landslide on Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the track onto the Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Regional Roads Victoria has undertaken geotechnical investigations at the site and implemented traffic management measures limiting Bogong - High Plains Road to one lane in this area, with reduced speed also in place.
  • With heavy rainfall forecast for the region this week and into next week, a full closure of Bogong - High Plains Road is in effect from midday on Wednesday 12 October. 
  • From now, access to and from Falls Creek will only be allowed for emergency services and essential services. 
  • When the road will re-open has not been determined and will depend on weather conditions and ongoing management of the landslide risk.
  • Regional Roads Victoria will continue to monitor the landslide risk and potential impact on Bogong - High Plains Road.
  • Geotechnical experts will complete assessments of the site and determine the best course of action to address the risk
Stay safe by avoiding fallen trees and powerlines, blocked or damaged roads and the area in general. Be aware of other hazards caused by the landslide.

The Bogong High - Plains Road at Bogong IS NOW CLOSED from Mt Beauty as planned from midday on Wednesday 12 October in anticipation of poor weather worsening the landslide.

Road users can no longer enter or exit Falls Creek or the Bogong Village from either direction on the Bogong High - Plans Road. 

What you should do:
  • If you have chosen to remain, expect to be unable to leave for three days until the extreme weather has passed and the road is safely cleared. 
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landside occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, powerlines and poles.
  • If you are inside, move to the part of building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • Stay away from the impacted area to allow emergency services to help affected communities.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Driving:
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road.
  • There is now no access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong - High Plains Road is closed. 
  • The Bogong High Plains Road on the other side of Falls Creek remains closed due to snow and will likely remain that way for several more weeks.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226.
  • VicEmergency app.
  • Facebook or Twitter (#viclandslide).
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream.
  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 6 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 3 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 14 October 2022.
  •  Insignificant rainfall totals are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 15 October 2022.
  • The Watts River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 4 mm since 09:00 AM Friday 14 October 2022. 
  • Insignificant rainfall totals are forecast for the catchment for Saturday 15 October 2022. 

Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream
  • The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream peaked at 5.41 metres at 10:10 AM on Saturday (15 October 2022). 
  • It is currently at 5.32 metres, exceeding the Moderate Flood Level (5.10 metres), and falling
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 06:00 am or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Warracknabeal and Yarriambiack Creek.

It is estimated that flooding in Warracknabeal and along Yarriambiack Creek is likely to be a 1 in 50 year flood event.

Warracknabeal 
Flooding may impact the Warracknabeal Fauna Park at Apex Park (Craig Ave) and Warracknabeal Caravan Park. 

Several buildings south of Warracknabeal may be impacted by flooding above floor along Dumbuoy Road, (west of Cemetery Road) . 

Deep flooding may cut access to roads along Yarriambiack Creek in and surrounding Warracknabeal, these include: 
  • Jeparit-Warracknabeal Road,
  • Cemetery Road 
  • Dumbuoy Road.  
Yarriambiack Creek 
Flooding along Yarriambiack Creek between the Wimmera River and Warracknabeal may impact buildings and isolate houses. 

Road where houses may be isolated along Yarriambiack Creek may include 
  • Roses Road, 
  • Henty Highway, 
  • Greenhills Road, 
  • Drillers Road, 
  • Daveys Road. 
Deep flooding may cut access to roads along Yarriambiack Creek (from the Wimmera River to Warracknabeal), these include: 
  • Horsham-Minyip Road, 
  • Henty Highway at Kellalac, 
  • Minyip-Dimboola Road, 
  • Ailsa Road    
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • For people that may be isolated please ensure you have 72 hours of provisions. People may be isolated for 2 to 3 days.

Visits the SES website to find information about Sandbagging and Collection points.

Victorians impacted by the floods can call the Flood Recovery Hotline 1800 560 760 to access available support.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 03:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.name: All Clear
properties.webBody:
The flood evacuation warning for Parfitt Road, Wangaratta has been lifted.  

Council & DEWLP Geological Engineers have inspected the levee bank and assessed it is unlikely to fail.

Emergency Services will continue to monitor the areas of concern on the levee as the flood waters reside.

Residents within the Parfitt Rd Levee are encouraged to continue to follow their flood plan.


It is now safe for residents to return home.

You should monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Please keep children away from playing within floodwaters .
What you should do: 
  • Stay alert - dangerous conditions caused by flooding in Wangaratta may still remain.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Emergency services are in the Wangaratta local area due to ongoing flooding.
  • Damage to surrounding roads and buildings caused by flooding may still exist in your area.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Emergency contacts:
  • For life threatening emergencies phone Triple Zero (000).
  • For flood and storm emergency assistance from the SES phone 132 500.
Stay informed: 
  • Go to www.emergency.vic.gov.au.
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Phone the VicEmergency Hotline to talk to someone about this warning on 1800 226 226 (freecall).
  • People who are deaf, hard of hearing, or who have a speech/communication impairment can contact VicEmergency Hotline via the National Relay Service on 1800 555 677.
  • For help with English, phone the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to telephone VicEmergency Hotline. If you know someone who cannot speak English, provide them with this number.
  • Download the VicEmergency app or follow VicEmergency on Twitter (#vicfloods) or Facebook.

properties.name: Community Information
properties.location: Coast - Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border
properties.webBody:
This message is being issued for for coastal water from Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border.

  • The levels of blue green algae within the Gippsland Lakes have decreased to below safe contact thresholds. The entire Gippsland Lakes system and ocean is now safe for recreational contact with the water.
  • It is important to note that advice regarding the consumption of specific seafood remains in place.
  • The latest seafood sample results show that Nodularin concentrations remain elevated in crab and bug samples collected within and outside the Gippsland Lakes. Additional seafood samples are being organised for collection and analysis.
Do not eat prawns from affected waters.

These prawns may have come from the Gippsland Lakes and Ninety Mile Beach area and may contain toxins from the recent blue green algae bloom.

COMMUNITY INFORMATION - BLUE GREEN ALGAE
Incident Location: Coast - Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border
Issue Date: Monday 19 September 2022, 03:43 pm
Next Update: Wednesday 19 October 2022, 03:40 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/21848/moreinfo

This message is being issued for for coastal water from Marlo to the Victoria-New South Wales Border. 

- The levels of blue green algae within the Gippsland Lakes have decreased to below safe contact thresholds. The entire Gippsland Lakes system and ocean is now safe for recreational contact with the water.
- It is important to note that advice regarding the consumption of specific seafood remains in place. 
- The latest seafood sample results show that Nodularin concentrations remain elevated in crab and bug samples collected within and outside the Gippsland Lakes. Additional seafood samples are being organised for collection and analysis. 



Do not eat prawns from affected waters.

These prawns may have come from the Gippsland Lakes and Ninety Mile Beach area and may contain toxins from the recent blue green algae bloom.

Do to not consume prawns caught within 10 nautical miles of the shore between Mcloughlins Beach and the Victoria-New South Wales border.

MAJOR FLOODING POSSIBLE AT HORSHAM FROM MONDAY MORNING

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT QUANTONG BRIDGE

Major flooding is occurring along the Wimmera River at Glenorchy in response to heavy rainfall during Thursday and overnight into Friday. 

The river level is currently peaking around 5.0 metres, which is below the January 2011 peak of 5.03 metres.Minor flooding is likely to develop at Horsham from Sunday morning. 

Further rises are expected and major flooding is possible from Monday morning.

Wimmera River to Glenorchy 
Major flooding is occurring along the Wimmera River to Glenorchy.

The Wimmera River at Glenorchy is currently at 4.99 metres and steady, with major flooding. The Wimmera River at Glenorchy is expected to remain above the major flood level (4.80 m) during Saturday.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir.

  • MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT APPIN SOUTH FROM SUNDAY MORNING AND KERANG FROM OVERNIGHT MONDAY. PEAK FLOOD LEVELS SIMILAR TO JAN 2011 POSSIBLE. 
  • MAJOR FLOODING IS CONTINUING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LODDON WEIR
  • Minor to major flooding is occurring in the Loddon River catchment, with renewed rises from recent rainfall and peaks from recent flooding continuing to travel downstream. 
  • Major flooding is continuing at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir, and is likely to extend downstream to Appin South from Sunday morning and to Kerang from overnight Monday into Tuesday. River levels are likely to peak at similar levels to the January 2011 flood event. 
  • Moderate flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Laanecoorie Reservoir and minor flooding is occurring Downstream (D/S) Cairn Curran.
Loddon River Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir: 

Moderate flooding is occurring along the Loddon River Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir.

The Loddon River D/S Laanecoorie is currently at 4.86 metres and falling, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River D/S Laanecoorie is likely to remain above the moderate flood level (3.00 m) for the next few days.

Floodwaters are currently receding at Newbridge and Bridgewater
Laanecoorie to Loddon Weir will continue to be impacted. 

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous.
What you should do: 

  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • A relief centre is located at Bridgewater Memorial Hall, 37 Eldon Street,  Bridgewater on Loddon.
  • Some homes in Bridgewater are likely to be isolated. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Some areas will be likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 10:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for the city of Shepparton. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

  • This updated evacuation advice replaces the Emergency Warning issued at 6pm, due to reviewing the flood conditions.
  • It is now recommended that residents and visitors in Shepparton evacuate between now and 11pm Saturday 15th October to the Shepparton Showgrounds, High St, Shepparton.
  • This advice particularly applies to: 
From the river along Daldy Rd east to the Barmah-Shepparton Rd then south to the transmission lines crossing the highway then west and south to Wanganui Rd; across to Mercury Ct then south on the Numurkah Rd  to Halpin Cres; then west up to Furze Ave, along Newton Cres, up to Hicken Cres to Fehey St down to Balaclava Rd across to Gowrie St, up to Alambie St then down to The Blvd; follow The Blvd down to Quinan Pde to the Midland Highway down Welsford St to the railway line. North up the railway line to Swallow St then down to Haves St then down Hare St, Sanderson St, Wilmot Rd, Bradford Rd, Palmer Rd to Broken River Drive. Across to the Goulburn Valley Highway across to forest Rd, down to Settlers Dr and across to the Goulburn River. 

An area bounded by Kittles Rd, the river, Wanganui Rd and west of Kingfisher Dve, Pelican Crt and Curlew Pl should remain unaffected however it will be isolated by waters to the east and north. 
If you are located in Shepparton, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately to the Shepparton Showgrounds.
If you are already surrounded by floodwater, it is too late to leave.
Never enter floodwater.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • The relief centre that has been opened at Shepparton Showgrounds. 
  • Family or friendsâ€™ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
The Midland Hwy also known as the Mooroopna Causeway between Mooroopna and Shepparton is now CLOSED.

When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

This warning is current to 11pm Saturday 15th October. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Based on historic data, this flood is likely to have a similar impact as the 1974 flood event.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 11:30 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 

Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

Minor flooding occurring at Mongans Bridge, Kiewa and Bandiana

Moderate flooding has eased at Bandiana Saturday morning. Minor flooding is currently occurring at Mongans Bridge, Kiewa (Main Stream) and Bandiana.


Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge

  • The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 3.40 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 
  • The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is expected to remain above the minor flood level (3.30 m) during Saturday and into Sunday.
  • The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 3.10 metres and falling slowly, with minor flooding. 
  • The Kiewa River at Bandiana is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.80 m) during Saturday and Sunday.
This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 7.20 PM Friday October 14. 
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Shallow flooding over significant areas of low lying farmland and local access routes.
  • Minor roads may be closed and low level bridges submerged.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Rochester. 

  • Major flooding occurring along the Campaspe River at Rochester.
  • A relief centre has been opened at Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Road, North Bendigo. The facility may have capabilities for small domestic pets, preferably in cages.
  • This is an update, replacing the Emergency Warning issued on 15 October at 7:06am.
Rochester is currently impacted with major flooding. If you are located in this area you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations.
  • Widespread flooding of the area.
  • Numerous roads are closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 17/10/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for properties locations listed below in the Kialla West area. 

  • An Evacuation Warning remains current, but it is now too late to leave. 
  • The flood is expected to impact properties listed below at overnight Saturday, which means there is no longer enough time to safely leave your property.
The Midland Hwy also known as the Mooroopna Causeway between Shepparton and Mooroopna will be CLOSED from 7pm tonight, 15 October
It is now too late to leave for people in properties listed below in the Kialla West area. If you have not evacuated, you should shelter in the highest location possible.

Union Rd West from just east of the Goulburn River east onto Union Rd to just east of the Archer Rd south intersection (northern side); from the northern end of Archer Rd South east across to Central Kialla Rd across to Trevaskis Rd (includes McKernan Rd west of Trevaskis Rd) to the East Goulburn Main Channel. North along the Channel to Irish Creek then northwest to Trevaskis Rd then west to Central Kialla Rd (includes the Kialla Golf Club) then northwest to Mitchell Rd along Seven Creeks to the Shepparton-Seymour Rd. Then south down behind the cemetery down to Moira Drive west across to the Goulburn River (includes Moira Park Scout Camp) then east back to the Shepparton-Seymour Rd and to Seven Creeks. South along Seven Creeks to just north of Union Rd then west to No2 Channel.
What you should do: 

If you have not already evacuated: 
  • Stay where you are and shelter in the highest location possible. 
  • Be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time. 
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance. 

If you have already evacuated: 
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued. 
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

This evacuation warning is likely to remain in place for several days and will be reviewed daily
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flood levels remain above that of a single-story home. 
  • Based on historic data, this flood is likely to have a similar impact as the 1974 flood event
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
  • For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • For relief and recovery information go to www.emergency.vic.gov.au/relief.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.

Flood Warning Number: 13
MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR AND MURCHISON.
MAJOR FLOODING LIKELY AT SHEPPARTON FROM OVERNIGHT SATURDAY INTO SUNDAY, WITH A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 12 METRES POSSIBLE ON TUESDAY
Flooding is easing along the upper Goulburn River and its tributaries. Major flooding is continuing from Seymour downstream.
Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. Major flooding has also developed at Murchison late Friday afternoon. Major flooding is likely to extend downstream to Shepparton during overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.
The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 11.90 metres and rising, with major flooding. The Goulburn River at Murchison is likely to peak near 12.00 metres Saturday afternoon.
The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 10.22 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to exceed the moderate flood level (10.70 m) Saturday afternoon. The river level is likely to exceed the major flood level (11.00 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday and may reach around 12.00 metres during Tuesday, slightly below the 1974 flood event level of 12.09 metres.
Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton:
Minor flooding may occur along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton during Saturday overnight into Sunday.
The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 8.44 metres and rising slowly, below the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge may reach the minor flood level (9.00 m) overnight Saturday into Sunday. Further rises to the moderate and major flood levels are expected early next week as upstream floodwaters arrive.
Floodwaters in the Murray and Campaspe Rivers are rising, which is impacting some areas of Echuca.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.  
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Review the Local Mooroopna and Shepparton Flood Guide at http://https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 02:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • For information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Access the Mooroopna and Shepparton Local Flood Guide from ses.vic.gov.au for localised information.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
The Emergency Warning to Evacuate, following flooding at Maribrynong River in Maribyrnong has been lifted and it is Safe to Return.

Dangerous hazards including floodwater, mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees may still be present. 

Only residents or people with a pecuniary interest should be in the area.
It is now safe to return the evacuated area to assess impacts as the threat is reduced. Be aware of any hazards that may still exist in the warning area. 
What you should do when returning:
  • Check for building damage before you enter
  • Have all electrical and gas equipment professionally tested before use.
  • Clean and dry out the building as soon as possible.
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.
  • Stay away from damaged and flooded buildings, fallen or damaged trees and powerlines, and damaged roads until authorities advise they are safe.
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 

Contact your local council or go to www.emergency.vic.gov.au/relief for relief and recovery information.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for the King River at Docker Rd.
 
MAJOR FLOODING TO CONTINUE AT WANGARATTA AND DOCKER ROAD BRIDGE DURING SATURDAY

Major flooding has peaked along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge during Friday afternoon and downstream on the Ovens River at Wangaratta overnight Friday into Saturday.

Major flooding is occurring along the King River. The King River D/S Lake William Hovell is currently around 2.00 metres and falling, with minor flooding. The King River D/S Lake William Hovell is likely to remain above the minor flood level (1.80 m) during Saturday.

The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is currently at 4.15 metres and steady. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge is likely to remain above the major flood level (4.10 m) during Saturday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Farmers should keep livestock and machinery on higher ground until flooding eases.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

Impacts in your area:

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • At the Moderate Flood Level (3.95m), low-lying farmland is likely to be affected. Docker-Carboor Road is closed between Wangaratta-Whitfield Road & Oxley-Meadow Creek Road due to flooding.
  • Other local roads may be closed due to flooding.
  • At the Major Flood Level (4.1m), flooding will increase in farmland along the river.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 15/10/2022 11:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

This is a Final Flood Watch for Thomson River
 
Final Flood Watch for Northern and parts of Southern Victoria 

A cold front has crossed Victoria resulting in a widespread heavy falls during Wednesday into early Friday. 

Catchments in the Flood Watch area are very wet and river levels are elevated within the catchments. 

No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days. 

Widespread minor to major flooding is occurring in several catchments across Victoria. 
Major flood warnings are current for the Avoca, Broken, Campaspe, Goulburn, Ovens and King, Loddon, Wimmera, Seven and Castle Creeks. Moderate flood warnings are current for the Barwon River, Mt Emu Creek and Yarra River. A minor to major flood warning is current for the Murray River. Minor flood warnings are current for the Bunyip, Kiewa, Latrobe, Mitchell, Werribee and Broken Creek. 

Flooding is no longer expected in the following catchments: 

Thomson River 
South Gippsland Rivers
The threat of flooding is reduced. You can now return to normal activity, but be aware of any hazards that may still exist in the warning area.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for parts of Echuca and Echuca Village. If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 
 
  • Flooding is expected to impact residents who's properties surround the Campaspe River from this afternoon onwards. 
  • Residents in Echuca Village can expect to be impacted over the coming days.
If you are located in the warning areas, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 

  • Family or friendsâ€™ homes located in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Bendigo relief centre, Bendigo Showgrounds, Holmes Road Bendigo
  • If you require assistance with transport to Bendigo, please attend the Echuca South Sport stadium, 244 High Street Echuca.
  • Is strongly recommended you evacuate during daylight hours.

The safest evacuation route is by Kotta, Lockington, Elmore (Via Elmore Mitiamo Road). Then travel directly to Bendigo via the Midland Highway. 

Follow link for Google Maps Link to route Evacuation Route

When you leave, remember to take your pets, mobile phone and medications. 

Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 

If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 

If you stay: 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 

This warning is current to 7.00pm Saturday 15th October 2022. If you do not evacuate before this time, your property may be isolated or inundated with water and it may be too late to leave. 

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate is dangerous and may put your life at risk. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Areas near the affected location may lose services including power, water, sewerage and phone coverage due to flooding.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 09:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.

Flood Warning Number: 14
MAJOR FLOODING NOW OCCURRING AT SHEPPARTON WHERE A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 12.00 METRES IS POSSIBLE ON TUESDAY
MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR AND MURCHISON
Major flooding has developed along the Goulburn River at Shepparton during Saturday afternoon, with levels rising rapidly due to tributary inflows from the Broken River and Seven and Castle Creeks. River levels will continue to rise as the main flood peak arrives along the Goulburn River from Murchison, with a peak around 12.00 metres possible on Tuesday.
Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. Major flooding is currently peaking around 12.00 metres at Murchison.
Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.
Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:
Major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.
The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 4.96 metres and steady, just below the major flood level (5.0 metres). The Goulburn River Lake Eildon is likely to remain around 4.96 metres during Saturday.
The Goulburn River at Seymour peaked at 8.26 metres around 03:00 am Friday 14 October and is currently at 7.22 metres and falling, with major flooding. The Goulburn River at Seymour is expected to remain above the major flood level (7.00 m) during Saturday.
Impacts continue along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour. 

If you are located in low lying areas or close to a waterway you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

  • Refer to the Seymour local flood guide at ses.vic.gov.au for more information.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
  • A relief centre is open at the Seymour Sports and Aquatic Centre, Pollard St. Seymour.
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 

Emergency services may not be able to help you if you decide to stay. 
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level is occurring in many locations.
  • Widespread flooding of the area is occurring.
  • Main and local roads are closed at various locations throughtout the catchment. For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
Seymour
  • At 8.37m, this flood is regarded as a 1% flood, which means there is a 1% chance of a flood this size or larger occurring in any given year. At this height, 288 properties are affected with 263 flooded above floor level
  • This flood has exceeded the levels recorded in the May 1974 flood which reached a height of 7.64m. At this height, 187 homes and businesses were affected with flooding above the height of floor level. There were 279 homes and businesses that become isolated by flooding due to roads and property flooding.
  • At the major flood level (7.0m), Kings Park flooded and Goulburn Valley Highway closed between Seymour Toyota and Redbank Road. 
  • In 1993, when the river reached a height of 6.65m, at least five houses in Butler and Emily Streets were flooded above the height of floor level. Properties in Edward, Emily, Hanna, Tierney, Alexander, High, Tallarook and Wallace streets also become isolated and surrounding areas were flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 12:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune into ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.
  • Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • navigating available supports mental health and wellbeing support
  • The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday. Call 1800 560 760If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance Call 000If your home is about to flood Call VICSES on 132 500Rural Roads

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

EMERGENCY WARNING - RIVERINE FLOOD - Move to Higher Ground
Incident Location: Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour
Issue Date: Saturday 15 October 2022, 06:23 pm
Next Update: Sunday 16 October 2022, 12:30 am

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/23420/moreinfo

This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.

Flood Warning Number: 14
MAJOR FLOODING NOW OCCURRING AT SHEPPARTON WHERE A MAJOR PEAK AROUND 12.00 METRES IS POSSIBLE ON TUESDAY
MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT SEYMOUR AND MURCHISON
Major flooding has developed along the Goulburn River at Shepparton during Saturday afternoon, with levels rising rapidly due to tributary inflows from the Broken River and Seven and Castle Creeks. River levels will continue to rise as the main flood peak arrives along the Goulburn River from Murchison, with a peak around 12.00 metres possible on Tuesday.
Major flooding has peaked at Seymour above the record flood from May 1974 of 7.64 metres. Major flooding is currently peaking around 12.00 metres at Murchison.
Forecasts for downstream locations will be updated regularly as upstream locations peak.
Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour:
Major flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour.
The Goulburn River downstream of Lake Eildon is currently at 4.96 metres and steady, just below the major flood level (5.0 metres). The Goulburn River Lake Eildon is likely to remain around 4.96 metres during Saturday.
The Goulburn River at Seymour peaked at 8.26 metres around 03:00 am Friday 14 October and is currently at 7.22 metres and falling, with major flooding. The Goulburn River at Seymour is expected to remain above the major flood level (7.00 m) during Saturday. 


Impacts continue along the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour. 

If you are located in low lying areas or close to a waterway you are in danger - act now to protect yourself and move to higher ground. 

Leaving now is the safest option, before conditions become too dangerous.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Mt Emu Creek to Skipton.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT SKIPTON

Major flooding has eased along the Mt Emu Creek at Skipton and moderate flooding is occurring. Rainfall has eased and no significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days. 

In the coming days river rises are expected downstream of Skipton as the flood peak travels from Skipton to the confluence with the Hopkins River. 

Mt Emu Creek to Skipton: 
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Mt Emu Creek to Skipton. 

Mt Emu Creek at Skipton measured 4.87 metres at 6pm on Saturday 15th October and falling slowly, with moderate flooding. Mt Emu Creek at Skipton is likely to fall below the moderate flood level (4.70 m) Saturday evening.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 16/10/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.

Flood Recovery Hotline - 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.  

If your home is flooding and you need emergency assistance, call 000 
If your home is about to flood, call VICSES on 132 500

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
